# CITIZENSHIP – PART II OF THE INDIAN CONSTITUTION  
## (Articles 5–11) | UPSC GS-II Notes (Lakshmikanth-based)

---

## 1. Meaning of Citizenship

- Citizenship denotes **full membership of the State**.
- Citizens enjoy **civil and political rights**.
- **Part II of the Constitution** deals only with citizenship **at the commencement of the Constitution**.
- Date of commencement: **26 January 1950**
- Permanent provisions are **left to Parliament**.

---

## Articles at a Glance

| Article | Subject |
|-------|--------|
| Article 5 | Citizenship at commencement |
| Article 6 | Migrants from Pakistan to India |
| Article 7 | Migrants to Pakistan |
| Article 8 | Indians residing outside India |
| Article 9 | Voluntary acquisition of foreign citizenship |
| Article 10 | Continuance of citizenship |
| Article 11 | Parliament’s power over citizenship |

---

## 2. Article 5 – Citizenship at the Commencement

A person is a citizen of India at the commencement of the Constitution if he/she:

### Conditions
- Had **domicile in India**, and
- Satisfied **any one** of the following:
  - Born in India
  - Either parent born in India
  - Ordinarily resident in India for **5 years immediately preceding 26 January 1950**

### Key Concepts
- **Domicile** → Permanent home with intention to reside permanently
- **Ordinary residence ≠ temporary stay**

> **Note:**  
> Article 5 applies **only to persons living in India on 26 January 1950**

### Flowchart: Article 5
Person on 26 Jan 1950
|
Does the person have DOMICILE in India?
|
-----+-----
| |
NO YES
| |
Not citizen |
v
Fulfilled ANY ONE condition?
- Born in India
- Parent born in India
- Resident for 5 years
|
Citizen of India
---

## 3. Article 6 – Citizenship of Migrants from Pakistan to India

Applies to persons who migrated **from Pakistan to India**.

### Context
- Result of **Partition (1947)**

### Common Condition
- Person / parent / grandparent **born in India**  
  (as per Government of India Act, 1935)

### Based on Date of Migration

| Date of Migration | Requirement |
|------------------|------------|
| Before 19 July 1948 | Ordinarily resident in India since migration |
| On / After 19 July 1948 | Registration as citizen required |

#### Registration Requirements
- Registration before commencement of Constitution
- Resident in India for **at least 6 months** before application

**Why 19 July 1948?**
- Introduction of **permit system** for migration

### Flowchart: Article 6
Migrated from Pakistan to India
|
Born in India (self/parent/grandparent)?
|
-----+-----
| |
NO YES
| |
Not citizen |
v
Date of migration?
----+--------------------
| |
Before 19 July 1948 On/After 19 July 1948
| |
Ordinarily resident Registered + 6 months
since migration residence in India
| |
-----------+--------------
|
Citizen of India

---

## 4. Article 7 – Migrants to Pakistan

- A person who migrated **from India to Pakistan after 1 March 1947**:
  ❌ **Not a citizen of India**

### Exception
- If the person returned to India with a **permit for resettlement or permanent return**
- Treated as migrant **after 19 July 1948**
- Covered under **Article 6**

### Flowchart: Article 7
Migrated from India to Pakistan
after 1 March 1947?
|
-----+-----
| |
NO YES
| |
Apply Art 5/6 |
v
❌ Not a citizen of India
|
Returned with permit for
resettlement / permanent return?
|
-----+-----
| |
NO YES
| |
❌ Not citizen Treated as migrant
after 19 July 1948
|
Apply Article 6


### Why 1 March 1947?
- Marks beginning of **large-scale Partition-related migration**
- Indicates **change in domicile and political allegiance**

### Constituent Assembly Debates (Value Addition)
- **Dr. B.R. Ambedkar**:
  - Citizenship must reflect **clear intention and allegiance**
- Objectives:
  - Avoid **dual claims**
  - Prevent **citizenship ambiguity** during Partition

---

## 5. Article 8 – Indians Residing Outside India

- Applies to persons of **Indian origin residing outside India**
- Must be **registered** by Indian diplomatic or consular representative

### Examples
- Indians settled in:
  - Burma
  - Sri Lanka
  - Malaya
  - UK
  - Africa

### Flowchart: Article 8
Residing outside India
|
Indian origin (self/parent/grandparent)?
|
-----+-----
| |
NO YES
| |
Not citizen |
v
Registered with Indian
diplomatic/consular authority?
|
-----+-----
| |
NO YES
| |
Not citizen Citizen of India


---

## 6. Article 9 – Voluntary Acquisition of Foreign Citizenship

- If a person **voluntarily acquires citizenship of a foreign State**:
  ❌ Ceases to be an Indian citizen

### Important Points
- India **does not allow dual citizenship**
- Meaning of “voluntary acquisition” decided by **Parliament’s law**

> **Current relevance:**  
> OCI ≠ Indian citizenship

### Flowchart: Article 9
Citizen under Articles 5 / 6 / 8
|
Voluntarily acquired
foreign citizenship?
|
-----+-----
| |
NO YES
| |
Citizen ❌ Ceases to be
Indian citizen


---

## 7. Article 10 – Continuance of Citizenship

- Every person who is a citizen under Articles 5–8:
  - Continues to be a citizen
  - Subject to laws made by Parliament

> Citizenship is **not absolute**

---

## 8. Article 11 – Power of Parliament

- Parliament has power to make laws on:
  - Acquisition of citizenship
  - Termination of citizenship
  - All matters relating to citizenship

### Flowchart: Articles 10 & 11
Citizen under Articles 5–8
|
Continues as citizen
(Article 10)
|
Subject to Parliamentary law
|
Parliament empowered
(Article 11)
|
Citizenship Act, 1955

### Citizenship Act, 1955 – Modes
- By birth
- By descent
- By registration
- By naturalization
- By incorporation of territory

---

## 9. Important Timeline (Prelims Focus)

- **1 March 1947** → Migration to Pakistan (Article 7)
- **19 July 1948** → Permit system introduced
- **26 January 1950** → Constitution comes into force

---

## ONE-LINE UPSC SUMMARY

> *Part II of the Constitution defines who were citizens of India at the commencement of the Constitution, while empowering Parliament to regulate citizenship thereafter.*

